{"key":"processedPost-13800985","value":{"id":13800985,"first":13800926,"last":13801005,"when":1295274756,"utime":"01/17/11 04:32 PM","content":"It sounds like you have a really good pressure cooker.&nbsp; <br />My AA75X sterilizers pull a good vacuum after they cool down too.&nbsp; I let the Pressure cooker cool to nearly room temperature, and then set it in front of the flow hood before I pop the valve to allow air to enter.&nbsp; If you don't have a flow hood, try laying a clean, damp towel over the opening.&nbsp; This should help filter the air as it enters.<br />You're right not to over-challenge your jar filters.&nbsp; Nature abhors a vacuum, so that air is going to equalize the pressure everywhere, and that means your jars will get an influx too.&nbsp; As an added measure, make sure your jar lids are on very tight, so that any air entering will be forced through the filters.<br />RR","title":"Re: PC vacuum on cooling, what to do?"}}